      "commandWord": "find",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "questionText": "The $n$th term of a sequence is $4n - 3$.\n\n(a) Find the 10th term.\n(b) Find the value of $n$ for which the $n$th term is 81.",
      "answerType": "expression",
      "correctAnswer": "(a) 37, (b) 21",
      "tolerance": null,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        { "mark": "B1", "desc": "(a) $4(10)-3 = 37$" },
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "(b) $4n-3=81 \\Rightarrow 4n=84$" },
        { "mark": "A1", "desc": "(b) $n=21$ cao" }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "(a) $n=10$: $4(10)-3 = 40-3 = 37$",
        "(b) $4n-3 = 81 \\Rightarrow 4n = 84 \\Rightarrow n = 21$",
        "Check: $4(21)-3 = 84-3 = 81$ ✓"
      ],
      "explanation": "Substitute directly for (a); solve the equation for (b)."
    },
    {
      "id": "E2-07-Q2",
      "type": "short-answer",
      "totalMarks": 4,
      "commandWord": "find",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "questionText": "The first four terms of a sequence are $5, 11, 19, 29, \\ldots$\nFind an expression for the $n$th term of this sequence.",
      "answerType": "expression",
      "correctAnswer": "$n^2 + n + 3$",
      "tolerance": null,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "Second differences found: $6-4=2$... first differences: $6, 8, 10$; second differences: $2, 2$" },
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "Quadratic form $an^2 + bn + c$ with $a = 1$ (half of second difference)" },
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "Comparing with sequence to find $b$ and $c$: $n=1$: $1+b+c=5$" },
        { "mark": "A1", "desc": "$n^2+n+3$ cao" }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "First differences: $11-5=6$, $19-11=8$, $29-19=10$",
        "Second differences: $8-6=2$, $10-8=2$ (constant → quadratic)",
        "$a = \\frac{2}{2} = 1$, so form $n^2 + bn + c$",
        "$n=1$: $1+b+c=5 \\Rightarrow b+c=4$",
        "$n=2$: $4+2b+c=11 \\Rightarrow 2b+c=7$",
        "Subtract: $b=3$; then $c=4-3=1$",
        "$n$th term: $n^2+3n+1$",
        "Check: $n=1$: $1+3+1=5$ ✓; $n=2$: $4+6+1=11$ ✓; $n=3$: $9+9+1=19$ ✓"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "$n^2 + 3n + 1$",
      "explanation": "Use second differences to identify a quadratic sequence, then solve for the coefficients."
    },
